1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 (4. f3 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 c4 (8... O-O 9. Bd3 c4 10. Bc2 Nc6 11. Ne2 Re8 12. O-O) 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. g4 O-O) 4... O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 c5 7. O-O Nc6 8. a3 Bxc3 9. bxc3 b6 10. cxd5 (10. Ne5) 10... exd5 { White has two plans on how to best develop his bishop. However, they both fall flat. } { [%cal Ga3a4,Gc1a3,Bd4c5,Bb6c5,Bc3c4,Bc1b2] } 11. Bb2 (11. a4 Re8 (11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Bg4 13. Ba3 Re8) 12. Ba3 c4 13. Bb1 Bg4 { [%csl Gc4,Gb6,Ga7,Ba4,Bc3] }) (11. dxc5 bxc5 12. c4 Rb8 $10 { Stops Bb2 } { [%cal Gb8b2] } 13. cxd5 Qxd5) 11... c4 { "Almost obligatory" to avoid dxc5 and c4 from white } 12. Bc2 Bg4 13. Qe1 (13. h3 Bh5 { [%cal Gh5g6,Gg6c2] }) 13... Ne4 (13... Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nh5 { The bishop pair and strong center make this fine for white. }) 14. Nd2 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Bh5 16. f3 Bg6 17. e4 Qd7 18. Rae1 dxe4? (18... Rfe8 19. exd5 (19. e5 b5 { Black gets sufficient counterplay in the usual manner. } { [%cal Ga7a5,Gb5b4] } 20. f4 Bxc2 21. Qxc2 f5 (21... a5 22. f5) 22. g4 g6 23. h4 a5 24. h5 Kg7 25. Qg2 fxg4 26. hxg6 hxg6 27. f5 gxf5 { With a wild attack to come. }) 19... Ne7! { [%cal Ge7d5] }) 19. fxe4 Rfe8 { [%cal Gd5e4] } 20. Qf4 (20. a4 Ne5 21. Ba3 Nd3 22. Bxd3 cxd3 23. Qxd3 Qxa4 $17) 20... b5 21. Bd1 Re7 22. Bg4 Qe8 23. e5 a5 24. Re3 Rd8 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gd4d5] } 25. Rfe1 { [%csl Ge6,Gd5] } 25... Re6!! { Sacrifices the exchange just to get a blockade on the light squares. Petrosian's play has all been about keeping the dark squared bishop behind his own pawns. } { [%cal Gc6e7,Ge7d5] } 26. a4 (26. Bxe6 fxe6 27. Rg3 Ne7 { [%cal Ge7d5] } 28. Rf1 Nd5) 26... Ne7! { [%cal Ge7d5] } (26... b4 27. d5 Rxd5 28. Bxe6 fxe6 29. Qxc4 $16) 27. Bxe6 fxe6 28. Qf1 { [%cal Gf1c4] } 28... Nd5 29. Rf3 Bd3 { Just look at this compensation black got for the exchange... } 30. Rxd3 { Basically forced if you want any activity at all. } 30... cxd3 31. Qxd3 b4 32. cxb4 (32. c4!? Nb6 { [%csl Ga4] } 33. Rc1 (33. d5 exd5 34. c5 Nxa4 35. Bd4 Qg6 { In multiple lines, engine prefers Qg6. Without the queens on the board, the passed b and a pawns are much more important as they can push through faster. } 36. Qxg6 hxg6 37. Ra1 Nc3! { [%cal Gc3e2,Ge2d4,Ge2g1] } 38. Kf2 Nb5! { [%cal Gb5d4] }) 33... Nxa4 34. Ba1 Qc6 (34... Qg6 35. Qxg6 hxg6 36. c5 { Everyone's got passed pawns! })) 32... axb4 { Effectively going in for a draw. } 33. a5 Ra8 34. Ra1 Qc6 35. Bc1 Qc7 (35... Rxa5!? 36. Rxa5 Qxc1+ 37. Qf1 Qe3+ 38. Kh1 h6 39. Ra8+ Kh7 40. Qb1+ g6 41. Ra7+ Kh8 42. h3 Qxd4 $18 { Bronstein says that "black does not stand worse" but basically every legal rook move is winning for white... }) 36. a6 Qb6 37. Bd2 b3 38. Qc4 h6 39. h3 b2 40. Rb1 Kh8 41. Be1 $10 { Draw agreed } { [%csl Gb2,Ga6] } 41... Rxa6 (41... Qxa6 42. Qxa6 Rxa6 43. Rxb2 Ra1 44. Kf2 { Also an equal endgame. The knight is slightly better than the bishop, but not enough to win. }) 42. Qc8+ Kh7 43. Qc2+ Kh8 44. Qc8+ 1/2-1/2


