1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 { At the time, people thought that this variation was lost for black. In fact, once Kasparov took up the mantle, this variation became the orthodox main main line. } { [%cal Gc6e7,Gf6d7,Gf7f5] } 8... Ne7 9. Ne1 Nd7 10. Be3 f5 11. f3 f4 12. Bf2 { [%csl Gc7,Gd6] } 12... g5 13. Nd3 (13. b4 Nf6 14. c5 { Interesting try }) (13. a4 a5 14. Nd3 b6 15. b4 axb4 16. Nxb4 { Atypical queenside play and white has a slight pull still here. }) 13... Nf6 14. c5 Ng6 15. Rc1 { [%cal Gg1h1,Gf1g1] } 15... Rf7 { [%cal Gg7f8,Gf7g7,Gc5c6,Gb7b6] } 16. Rc2 (16. Kh1 Bf8 17. Rg1 { A relatively new idea by white to defend the kingside before the attack even starts. }) 16... Bf8 { Recent theory developed at Mar de Plata tournament in 1953. "Recent" progress! } 17. cxd6 cxd6 { [%cal Gc3b5,Ga7a6] } 18. Qd2!? { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gf1c1,Gc3b5,Gb5c7] } (18. Nb5 a6 19. Nc7 { [%cal Gf2b6] } 19... Rxc7 20. Bb6 Ne8 21. Rxc7 Nxc7 22. Qc1 Bd7 23. Bxc7 Qe8 { An interesting engine line. }) 18... g4 { White should not be allowing g4 so easily. } 19. Rfc1 g3! 20. hxg3 fxg3 21. Bxg3 Nh5 22. Bh2 Be7 { [%cal Ge7g5] } 23. Nb1 (23. Qe1 Bg5) 23... Bd7 (23... Bg5?? 24. Rxc8!) 24. Qe1 Bg5 25. Nd2 Be3+ 26. Kh1 Qg5 27. Bf1 (27. Nc4 Bxc1 28. Qxc1 Qxc1+ 29. Rxc1 { Suggested by Bronstein. }) 27... Raf8 28. Rd1 b5 29. a4 a6 30. axb5 axb5 31. Rc7 Rg7 32. Nb3 Nh4 33. Rc2 Bh3!! { [%cal Gf8f3] } 34. Qe2 { [%cal Gh3g2,Gf1g2,Gh4g2,Ge2g2,Gg5h4] } (34. gxh3 Qg1+ 35. Bxg1 Rxg1+ 36. Kh2 Nxf3#) 34... Nxg2 (34... Nxf3 35. gxf3 Ng3+ 36. Bxg3 Qxg3 { [%cal Ge2h2,Gg3f3] } 37. Bxh3 Qxh3+ 38. Qh2 Qxf3+ $19 { [%cal Gf3d1] }) 35. Bxg2 Bxg2+ 36. Qxg2 Qh4 37. Qxg7+ Kxg7 38. Rg2+ Kh8 39. Ne1 Nf4 40. Rg3 Bf2 41. Rg4 Qh3 42. Nd2 h5 43. Rg5 Rg8 44. Rxg8+ Kxg8 $19 { No defense against mate. White resigned on move 43 during adjournment. } { [%cal Gf2g3,Gh3h2,Bf4e2,Be2g3,Rh3g2] } 0-1


