1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 (7. Nf5?! d5 $17) 7... Be7 8. Be3 Nbd7 9. O-O O-O 10. f3 (10. a4) 10... Qc7 11. Qe1 (11. a4) 11... b5 12. a3 (12. a4 b4 13. Nd5? (13. Na2 a5 14. c3 $10) 13... Nxd5 14. exd5 $17) 12... Nb6 13. Qf2 Rb8 { [%cal Gb6a4,Gb6c4] } 14. Rab1 Be6 15. Kh1 Nc4 (15... d5! 16. exd5 Nbxd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bc5 $17) 16. Bxc4 bxc4 17. Nc1 Rb7 18. N1a2 d5? (18... a5! { [%csl Gb4] }) 19. exd5 Bxd5 20. Nb4 Bxb4 21. axb4 Qc6 22. Bg5 Rd7 23. Rfe1 Re8 24. Rbd1 Nh5 { White has been able to maximize his pieces positioning in the same time that black } 25. Qh4 g6 26. Nxd5 (26. Rd2 $14 { [%cal Ge1d1] }) 26... Rxd5 27. Rxd5 Qxd5 28. Qe4 Qxe4 29. Rxe4 { The transition to an endgame favors white - now the weak queenside pawns can actually be attacked. } 29... f6 30. Be3 Rc8 31. g4 Ng7 32. g5!? { Committal, but interesting to break the position open for the bishop. } 32... Kf7 33. gxf6 Kxf6 34. Bd2 Nf5 35. Bc3 Nd4 36. f4 (36. Bxd4 exd4 37. Rxd4 c3 38. b3 Re8 $10 { [%cal Ge8e2] }) 36... Nxc2 37. Re2 Na1 38. Rxe5 (38. fxe5+ Ke6 39. Rf2 { looks good enough for a win according to Bronstein. }) 38... Kf7 39. Ra5 (39. f5 gxf5 40. Rxf5+ Ke6 { Computer line, but trading pawns brings it closer to a draw... }) 39... Nc2 40. Rxa6 Rb8 41. Rc6 Nxb4 42. Rc7+ (42. Rxc4 Nd5 43. Be5 Rb3 $10 { [%cal Gf7e6,Ge6f5] }) 42... Ke6 43. Rxc4 Nd3 (43... Nd5 44. Re4+ { [%csl Gf5,Bd6][%cal Ge4e5,Bc3e5] } 44... Kf7! $10) 44. b4 Rf8 $10 { Draw agreed. } 1/2-1/2


